  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (or \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by concealing its true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, tax evasion, and terrorism financing. Many countries have established strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations to combat this activity, often requiring financial institutions and other entities to implement measures to detect and report suspicious transactions.\n\nInternationally, organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for combating money laundering and the financing of terrorism, and many countries participate in cooperative efforts to prevent and prosecute money laundering activities.",
